JFrog = Universal Artifact Repository
        stores ALL types of artifacts
        in ONE place ✅

What JFrog Stores

✅ JAR files        → Java artifacts (Maven)
✅ Docker images    → container images
✅ npm packages     → Node.js
✅ Python packages  → pip
✅ Helm charts      → Kubernetes
✅ zip/tar files    → generic artifacts
✅ rpm/deb          → Linux packages
✅ Go modules       → Golang

JFrog in CI/CD Pipeline

Stage 1: Checkout
Stage 2: Build          → creates JAR ✅
Stage 3: Test
Stage 4: SonarQube
Stage 5: Push to JFrog  → store JAR ✅
Stage 6: Docker Build   → uses JAR from JFrog ✅
Stage 7: Push Docker    → store image in JFrog ✅
Stage 8: Deploy

JFrog vs ECR vs Nexus

JFrog Artifactory:
  ✅ universal (all types)
  ✅ Docker images
  ✅ JAR files
  ✅ Helm charts
  ✅ enterprise grade
  ✅ paid (expensive)

AWS ECR:
  ✅ Docker images only
  ✅ AWS native
  ✅ cheap
  ❌ only Docker

Nexus Repository:
  ✅ universal (all types)
  ✅ free open source
  ✅ similar to JFrog
  ❌ less features than JFrog

Jenkins + JFrog Example

stage('Push to JFrog') {
    steps {
        // Push JAR to JFrog
        sh """
            curl -u admin:password \
            -T target/myapp.jar \
            "https://myjfrog.jfrog.io/artifactory/libs-release/myapp/1.0/myapp.jar"
        """
    }
}

stage('Push Docker to JFrog') {
    steps {
        sh """
            docker tag myapp:${BUILD_NUMBER} \
            myjfrog.jfrog.io/docker/myapp:${BUILD_NUMBER}

            docker push \
            myjfrog.jfrog.io/docker/myapp:${BUILD_NUMBER}
        """
    }
}
